Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Key takeaways:

  1. There is a lot of highly correlated columns throughout the data. This is of limited use becuase:

    a. The highly correlated items are so similar that they almost meant the same thing. For example, the open, close, high and low don't mean the same thing but they are not causative of overall price changes. The best we can do here is get a model to follow this to see price changes up and down.

    b. The time factor. Usually with this sort of data there is a causal feature that doesn't exist in basic data like this. For example, if Elon Musk twittered something about a stock and people sold or purchased it without considering the value of the investment, or if the company start dumping toxic waste into the ocean and made people sick. The numbers here would play catch up, but they would not indicate the future.

  1. The options datatset essentially prices the future of stocks and other assets. This would be very useful for a machine learning algorithm, however in this case there is limited time and being able to compare the contract codes with the stock codes would take a fair bit of manual research and application. This is becuase there is a lot of conracts that without reasearching in detail, would likely be coded by asset, time, exchange, put and call parties and who knows what else. This is logical for the options traders and the exchange, but not useful for a quick machine learning algorithm which is what we are doing here. In essence, we are looking through this data in search of simplicity.
  1. Missing data. You will note the lovely missing data visualisation from missingno. This is a separate package that you have to install. It is lovely though. I found this from a lad taking lessons on machine learning on youtube, you will find the link in the bibliography. With that said, what can we learn from this? Well, the stock prices dataset is probably the easiest to use for a machine learning algorithm.
  1. Histograms and so on... There are not any nice normal distributions that would be useful for this model. Yes we could standardise, but I feel that regression models will be much better than classification models such as KNN or whatever. We have done a wonderful KNN as you will note, but as expected the result of the KNN is rather predictable, in that it is not accurate in predicting outcomes at all.

Note to the marker. Please feel free to run this workbook, however you will note that I did this in Google Colab. This is becuase there is not enough computing power for the average desktop to run the codes below as the datasets are rather large.
